properties.Descriptio: Corbett Building is home to the Portland State Business Accelerator entrepreneurial program. The Accelerator provides office and lab space plus various optional services for technology and science focused business startups.
CLSB brings together Portland State University (PSU), Oregon State University (OSU), and Oregon Health & Science University (OHSU) health and life sciences programming on a single campus.
The University Place Hotel and Conference Center is owned by Portland State University and provides hotel and meeting/event spaces.
University Technology Services’ main entrance is on the south-side, and is wheelchair accessible. The building consists of five floors above ground. UTS includes both office and classroom space.
The Science and Education Center is at the corner of SW 5th Avenue and Lincoln Street at the southern edge of the PSU campus. The building was acquired by PSU in 2002.
The Art Building is a Bauhaus style building on the east side of SW 5th Avenue between Lincoln and College Street and houses the School of Art and Design.

The Engineering Building is a LEED-NC Gold certified building concrete and glass, five-story building located on SW 4th Avenue just south of the Fourth Avenue Building and City of Portland Development Tower.

University Pointe is a student housing building that includes a fitness center, computer center, study lounges, social lounges, and retail establishments on the ground floor. It is LEED Gold certified.

properties.LONGNAME: Native American Student and Community Center
properties.Descriptio: The Native American Student and Community Center provides a location where Native American, Alaskan Native and Pacific Islander students connect to other students, faculty, staff and community members in an inclusive and supportive environment.
Broadway Residence Hall is a student residence with classrooms and a computer laboratory located on the second floor and retail space dominates the ground floor.
The Fourth Avenue Building is connected to the Engineering Building via its underground level. In between the two on the ground level is a seven-story tower that houses City of Portland offices.

Primarily a student residence hall, Ondine also includes a student lounge, conference and meeting space, university offices, a dining facility, a small parking facility, and shares its basement with 5th Avenue Cinema.

The University Center is located on the block between SW 6th, Harrison, 5th, and Hall. It has a parking garage and is home to the Student Health and Counseling which can be accessed from the corner of SW Sixth Avenue and SW Hall Street.
East Hall has served as an administrative and academic space since it was acquired by Portland State College in 1966. It is currently home to PSU's Office of International Affairs.

Shattuck Hall is a three-story, red brick school building that contains classroom space, multi-level open-plan studios, material workshops for fabrication, gallery spaces, seminar rooms, as well as administrative and faculty offices.

Parking Structure One was the first parking facility constructed for what was then Portland State College; its site was acquired through Portland Development Commission urban renewal funding during the College's rapid expansion period in the mid-1960s.
The renovated Peter W. Stott Center will include a new façade along the Park Blocks with a multi-purpose arena, new training room and adds several student lounges and study spaces.

Neuberger Hall is a five story structure located on Broadway between Harrison and Hall Street on the South Park Blocks of Portland State University campus and houses over a dozen academic departments.

The PSU Research Greenhouse consists of 4 independently controlled compartments, a head house, and a covered patio. The compartments are devoted exclusively to research projects by faculty in Biology, Physics, and Environmental Sciences and Resources.

The Academic and Student Recreation Center houses retail spaces, the Transportation and Parking office, the Viking Welcome Center, and the Student Recreation Center. ASRC also includes academic, student workspaces, retail businesses, and other spaces.
The Campus and Ground Trailer resides between the West Heating Plant and Peter Stott Center just south of the Community Recreation Field.
The West Heating Plant supplies steam for heat and chilled water for air conditioning through a tunnel system to the Stott Center, Millar Library, Science One, SRTC and Parkmill.

The Karl Miller Center houses the School of Business Administration There are three street level entrances to the building. Skybridge access leading to other campus structures are on the fourth floor.

The Millar Library is constructed around a historic copper beech tree planted circa 1892.  The Library’s mission is to advance the intellectual vitality, knowledge, and creativity of the Portland State University community.
The Crown Plaza Building is an off-campus office building with space leased by PSU. Crown Plaza is located between SW First, Clay, Naito, and Market; its main entrance is on First Avenue.

SMSU is PSU’s student union and includes a food court on the first floor; a games room in the basement; a ballroom for events on the third and fourth floors; and offices for student organizations, groups, and other services throughout the building.

The Urban Center Building is comprised of two connected buildings: The Urban Center is the larger eastern building that includes two retail spaces including the PSU Bookstore. The smaller western section of the building is the Wilson-DeShane Pavilion.
Blackstone is a PSU student residence hall that houses non-first year students.
The Campus Public Safety building is the site of the Campus Public Safety Office (CPSO).

The University Services Building has entrances on Montgomery and on 6th Avenue. USB is accessible from every level of Parking 2 except the basement; wheelchair accessible entries are located at the roof level of Parking 2 and on 6th Avenue.

Parking Structure Two is attached to the University Services Building (USB). A skybridge on the fourth floor connects to the Graduate School of Education, the Karl Miller Center, Smith Memorial Student Union, and Cramer Hall.
Market Center Building houses the Office of the President and serves as the central hub of PSU's administration.

Cramer Hall was the first building constructed explicitly for Portland State and is named after its first president. Cramer Hall houses a variety of departments and is connected to Lincoln an Smith via tunnels and skybridges.
Simon Benson House sits west across the Park Blocks from SMSU. The first floor is used for University and Community functions. PSU's Office of Alumni Relations is located on the second floor.
The Harrison Street Building is located along the Walk of the Heroines and houses the Center for Lakes and Reservoirs.
The North Greenhouse was originally constructed in 2001 for the Environmental Sciences department.

The South Greenhouse is a single story greenhouse on SW 10th Avenue south of the Science Research and Teaching Center (SRTC) and northeast of the Harrison Street Building where it shares the block with the Oak Savanna.
The Montgomery Residence Hall is used primarily as student housing but also houses the PSU Women's Resource Center.
Hoffmann Hall contains a multi-media lecture hall suitable for large classes and other assemblies.
The King Albert Residence Hall is a student residence facing east along the southern edge of SW Montgomery and 11th Avenue.
Although primarily a residence hall, Epler Hall's first floor is devoted to classroom, office space and the Little Vikings Child Care facility.
Lincoln Hall houses PSU's performing arts programs and includes several practice rooms, studios, auditoriums and theaters.

SRTC has four floors and two basement levels. An accessible covered sky-bridge extends from the second floor at the north end to the second floor of SB1. Wheelchair access to SRTC is located on both the southwest and southeast corners of the building.
The Saint Helens Residence Hall is a five-story student residence tucked into the curve of Blumel Hall, opposite Parking 3 to the west, and King Albert and the Stephen Epler Hall to the south.
Parkmill, formerly known as the Extended Studies Building (XSB) consists of two floors and a basement. Originally constructed in 1957, the building currently does not have an elevator.
Joseph C. Blumel Residence Hall is a nine-story student residence with two parking levels surrounding the Saint Helens Building.
The Blumel Bike Garage offers secure bicycle parking including card controlled access, surveillance cameras, and a self-service repair stand with tools and air pump.
The Parkway was originally constructed as an apartment building in 1932 until 1969 when PSU acquired it as a student residence.
Science Building 1 is a six-story building that contains science classrooms, offices and laboratories.
Harder House is a repurposed residential building that houses PSU’s Systems Science doctoral program.
The Stratford Residence Hall is a student residence located at the intersection of Eleventh and Market, facing Harder House to the east, and standing just north of Science Building 1.
The University Honors building is home to PSU's University Honors College and contains office space with a few small meeting rooms in the basement.

Parking Structure Three is a seven-level parking structure. Vehicles may enter and exit from 12th or 13th Avenues. Stairs are located at the center of the east side and at the southeast corner. There is an elevator on the east-side of the building.
The Helen Gordon Child Development Center provides students, faculty, and staff with high-quality, on-campus, early education and child care.

The Fifth Avenue Cinema and is Oregon's only student-run cinema, with the PSU Film Committee responsible for all programming and operations. The Fifth Avenue Cinema shares space with the College of Engineering and Computer Science (CECS).
